If you want to use the word tone, do you! BUT what we need to make sure we understand is…

💪A TONED body is a MUSCULAR body.

I have had women tell me, “I want to get toned, but not gain muscle.” So then they’re afraid to lift heavy weight, because they are afraid to build muscle.

Tone= having muscle definition by ⬆️gaining muscle and ⬇️dropping some body fat (for aesthetic purposes)

Don’t shy away from lifting heavier weights! 🏋🏽‍♀️

Scrolling through past CrossFit competition photos gives me so many different feels…proud, exhausted, impressed, nostalgic!

Sometimes the thoughts in my head during those workouts cycled like this…
-why did you do this
-you are a bad ass
-I’m so tired
-You got this 
-Are we done yet 
-wow, I’m strong
-ugh, this is heavy
-This feels good
-I’m out of my league 
-I’m trying my best
-my legs are toast
-I can totally keep going
-I want to stop
-LET’S ** GOOOOO

One thing that I do know is afterwards…I definitely grew as a person mentally and physically! And even if the picture doesn’t show it, there were moments of fun😉 (like having friends and family cheer you on or hitting a PR)

If you’ve never done anything that physically gets you out of your comfort zone…give it a try (or two)! If it’s not fun, try something else!

🌟Reminder: Your daily eating habits affect your body composition more than the 3-6hrs you train weekly.

Why is this important to note?
Because some people tell me they workout regularly and are not seeing much changes to their body composition numbers. You’ve heard the phrase, “You can’t out-train a poor diet.” 

This is why putting more focus on creating sustainable, healthy eating habits for yourself is key! This doesn’t mean you have to count calories or macros…it can be incorporating more veggies, increasing water intake, upping your protein consumption, cooking at home more, consuming less alcohol!

You do NOT need to overtrain or do double workouts as a solution…take a look at what’s going on in the kitchen first 👩🏽‍🍳

FYI…flat tummy powder isn’t the remedy for every stomach issue. It’s a great product for companies to have and market because it promises something that many people want (but results not guaranteed).

When I was dealing with SIBO, I had “health coaches” and salespeople reach out to me saying they had the perfect product to help my issues. And when you’re desperate for change or to feel better…you may be easily swayed…I get it and have felt that. 

Instead, I worked with a nutritionist and am currently working with a practitioner to help heal the situation and for future prevention.

Save your money and find a specialist to work with🩷

4 things I won’t do anymore (from prior experience)

1️⃣ cutting carbs: why not? I was grumpy and energy was low😑 Brain fog and decreased workout performance. 

2️⃣ meal replacement shakes: why not? I felt food deprived and would be hungry soon after (and more likely to binge eat later)

3️⃣ skipping meals (or delayed eating): why not? It messed with my stomach and caused gut issues🤢, as well as low energy and being hangry 

4️⃣ not prioritizing protein: why not? I would get hungry much faster after my meal. It was harder to maintain/build muscle.

What are some things that no longer work for you that you thought you needed to do for body composition, health, or performance when it comes to eating?

Have you been neglecting meaningful self-care???

If so, keep an eye out for these things that can happen when you do. 🚩

One question that my students have asked me is…when they go to the gym on their own, who can they ask to spot them for a heavier lift. 

Here are some ideas in this reel!

The biggest thing is to be mindful to not ask someone when they are in mid-set…wait until they finish their lift or movement 💪

I also opt to look for people who don’t have their headphones on, but in some cases many do, so you will  have to look for someone who isn’t mid lift, and give a little wave 👋 to say hi/get their attention and ask.

* if someone says, no, do not take it personally, and see if you can find someone else! 🩷

Depending on your gym, you may even see a trainer who works there (that isn’t working it with a client) for you to ask!

Summer break is my favorite time of the year and it gets so hard to go back because you get a taste of that freedom of getting to just exist and be able to do things during the day on your timeline. (and being able to go to the bathroom whenever you want Lol.)

You can not base someone’s health solely on their appearance or how much they weigh.

Just because someone looks really lean/muscular or has visible abs, does NOT mean that they are the epitome of health. If someone appears in a larger body, it does not automatically mean that they are unhealthy. 

We can’t see the whole picture. 

Some challenges people may be experiencing (at ANY size) that you can’t always see: 
-chronic illness 
-anxiety/depression 
-mental health disorders
-eating disorders
-high blood pressure
-drug or alcohol abuse
-resting heart rate
-heart rate recovery 
-cholesterol levels
-inflammation (ex. arthritis)
-asthma
-diabetes
-gastrointestinal issues
-reproductive health issues
And so much more. 

There are people who don’t appear to have a lot of visible muscle and they still have good health markers. 

Aesthetics do not give us the whole picture 💁🏽‍♀️

📣YOU CAN’T SPOT REDUCE FAT OR TARGET AREAS FOR FAT LOSS 🤷🏽‍♀️

If someone is selling you a workout plan or promoting movements to spot reduce…this is a 🚩 🚩🚩. (They want your money)

Believe me, if it worked…I would’ve had leaner thighs years ago when I was trying so hard for them 😂 

We all hold fat in certain areas depending on our genetics, sex, age, and other factors. Your nutrition intake will also play a role in this. 

Don’t focus on one area for training and neglect the rest of your body. Overall muscle training will have so many awesome benefits for your body!

This is the first upper body barbell movement I start with my students! (And it’s usually their favorite upper body lift!)

If you want to start barbell lifting…I highly recommend bench press! 

Having the support of the bench under you helps with confidence and there is less to worry about mechanics wise (compared to taking the barbell overhead in a strict press). 💪
